;; appendix-a-where-we-could-have-done-better.book.slatl
;; Book of CS Curriculum — Appendix A — Where we could have done better
;; Introspective honest appendix (paired with Appendix B). Not comparative.
;; the runtime's direct-address register. 25 items.

(appendix
  :book             "Book of CS Curriculum"
  :chapter-number   null
  :title            "Appendix A — Where we could have done better"
  :source-path      "curator/scheme-books/book-of-cs-curriculum/appendix-a-where-we-could-have-done-better.book.slatl"
  :size             12800
  :sha256           "ada-round-2-2026-07-14"
  :prose
"# Appendix A — Where we could have done better

Every language is a set of choices. Some of ours worked. Some of ours didn't. This appendix is our honest retrospective — not because comparison to other languages is the point (it isn't) but because someone reading Motoi Scheme deserves to know what we were thinking when we made the calls we made. If a decision was a compromise, we say so. If we're carrying technical debt, we say so.

Twenty-five items below. Same shape throughout: our call, our reasoning, our honest read on it. Paired with Appendix B (where we're happy with what we did) — equal weight, equal count.

## 1. `syntax-rules` macros rather than a full pattern-class expander

Our macro hygiene is `syntax-rules`-flavored — pattern-and-template rewriting with automatic renaming. We didn't build a full pattern-class expander with structured error reporting and syntax classes that compose. That was a scope decision made when the language was small and one person could hold the whole system in their head.

It bought us a simple macro system a kid can read in a chapter. It cost us diagnosability: when a macro-heavy program fails to expand, the error message often points at the expansion point rather than the misuse site. If we started over with the current team size, we'd invest in the fuller expander from day one. We know why other Lisps went the other way — that path gives them error messages we'd like to have.

## 2. Boxed numeric tower with per-op dispatch

Every arithmetic operation goes through a boxed dispatch — exact integers, rationals, inexact reals, complex — with type checks at each step. This buys us clean semantics: no silent integer-overflow wraparound, no float-versus-int coercion surprises, no size-of-int platform dependence.

It costs us throughput. Tight numerical loops run slower than they would in a language that specializes to machine integers. We knew this. For a language whose purpose is teaching and symbolic reasoning, we thought the semantic clarity was worth more. For a language whose purpose was numerical computing, we'd have made a different call.

## 3. `act`-based effect discipline rather than a full effect system

We chose to lean on `act` dispatch for permissioned verbs rather than building a full effect system. Effects would have given us finer-grained static tracking of what a function can do — read the disk, hit the network, mutate global state, spend money. `act` is coarser: it partitions verbs into free-tier and metered-tier and does runtime checks.

It's simpler for a kid to understand and for us to implement. It costs us: on days when a big cart's permission surface gets confusing, the coarseness shows. We know that call was a compromise.

## 4. No formal module system yet

There isn't a real module system yet. We lean on the reader's namespace, the SLAT reference registry, and a naming convention for verb libraries (`math/`, `stat/`, `plot/`, and so on). This is fine for a language whose entire runtime fits in a few megabytes and whose author community is small.

It scales badly. Modules with private-versus-public borders, versioned imports, and dependency graphs would help. We haven't shipped it. It's on the list.

## 5. Single-threaded cooperative concurrency

The runtime is single-threaded. Concurrency is via cooperative `async`/`await` in the host, not preemptive threads or processes. This buys us determinism: a cart runs the same way twice. It buys us simplicity: no shared mutable state, no locks, no data races.

It costs us: CPU-bound work can't use multiple cores. For the kid drawing a Mandelbrot set, that's a real cost. We chose it because the carts are I/O-bound (LLM calls, HTTP, disk) more than CPU-bound, and because determinism was worth more than throughput to us. A cart that draws slowly is fine. A cart that gives different answers twice is not.

## 6. Reader position tracking granularity

Source positions in our reader are tracked at the s-expression level, not at the sub-token level. So an error inside a long string literal or a complex numeric literal points at the whole literal, not at the character that broke it. This is fine for most programs and it kept the reader small (~300 lines).

It's occasionally annoying when debugging generated code. We know how to fix it. We haven't prioritized it because the annoyance is rare and the fix would double the reader's size.

## 7. Tail calls proper, but no reified tail frames

We do proper tail calls — a tail-recursive loop won't blow the stack — but we don't reify tail frames as first-class values. That means no continuation-based coroutines built out of tail frames the way some Schemes offer.

We chose the simpler tail-call semantics because the debugging story is cleaner (the stack trace is what happened, minus tail frames). It costs us some advanced control-flow constructs a fuller Scheme would give us for free. The kid reading SICP §4.3 will notice this if they try to port `amb` verbatim. We have `amb`, but we implemented it directly rather than deriving it from `call/cc`.

## 8. String-as-bytes-or-codepoints ambiguity in legacy verbs

Our strings are Unicode codepoints, but a handful of legacy verbs treat them byte-wise (mostly the ones that talk to HTTP headers and file I/O). We know which verbs those are. We keep them behaved by convention rather than by type.

If we started over we'd have two distinct types — `string` and `bytes` — with explicit conversion. This is something we do that we wish we didn't. The difference is too minor to screw everything up to fix.

## 9. Contracts as documentation, not first-class values

Verbs ship with contract strings in the SLAT reference — `:in`, `:out`, arity — and the loader checks arity at call time. They aren't first-class values you can compose, refine, or blame the way a full contract system would let you. The contracts are documentation-plus-arity-check, not runtime proofs.

This was a deliberate scope call: we wanted the reference to be readable prose more than we wanted the contracts to be executable theorems. We accept the tradeoff. A verb with a subtle precondition still has to document it in English.

## 10. Eager evaluation by default

Arguments to verbs are evaluated eagerly. We provide `delay` and `force` for lazy values, and streams as a library, but the default is strict. This is the Scheme tradition. It fits our audience — the kid sees the argument evaluated when she calls the function, no surprises.

It costs us the elegant infinite-stream idioms a lazy language gives you for free. We picked the tradition. We're not regretful, but we notice the cost when we write an interesting stream program and have to sprinkle `delay` through it.

## 11. Lists as the default sequence, vectors secondary

Lists are the default sequence. Vectors exist and are O(1) indexable, but the ecosystem — verbs, examples, teaching materials — leans list-first. This is Scheme heritage: `map`, `filter`, `fold` are list operations.

It costs us performance on large indexed workloads. We know a kid working on image processing will hit this. Our answer is 'use vectors for that,' which is fine but adds a learning bump. If we started over we might make vectors the primary sequence and lists the secondary. We didn't, because the SICP-shaped pedagogy assumes lists.

## 12. Single global namespace for verbs

All 1,157 registered verbs live in one global namespace, partitioned only by naming convention (`stat/mean`, `plot/line`). There's no formal module boundary preventing collision. This works because we curate the registry centrally.

It won't scale to a world where operators write their own verb libraries and share them. When that world arrives, we'll need namespaces. We haven't built them.

## 13. No first-class pattern matching primitive yet

The SLAT registry doesn't yet include a pattern-matching primitive — no `match` verb, no destructuring `let`. The building blocks (`car`, `cdr`, `assoc`, predicates) are all there, and small matchers can be written in ~30 lines, but a first-class matcher would make symbolic code much more readable.

This is a known gap. Programs that would benefit — differentiators, tree walkers, small interpreters — read as `cond`-and-`car`-and-`cdr` chains. We know that's clunky. It's queued.

## 14. Verb signatures authored, not derived

Verb signatures are declared in the SLAT reference as prose plus an arity number. They aren't derived from the JavaScript implementations. So if an implementation drifts from its declared signature, the two disagree and nothing yells until a test catches it. We enforce agreement by review, not by tooling.

If we started over we'd generate signatures from the implementation or vice versa. We didn't, because the reference is the source of truth for the language and we wanted humans to author it directly.

## 15. Continuations exist but aren't in the teaching path

`call/cc` is in the interpreter but not in the kid-facing teaching material. We expose the search primitives (`amb`, generators) that continuations enable, but we don't teach `call/cc` itself in the early chapters.

This was a pedagogical call: continuations are hard, and we thought exposure to the search primitives was worth more than exposure to the full underlying mechanism. A kid who reads SICP will learn `call/cc` from SICP; ours doesn't come with it out of the box.

## 16. Regex library shape borrowed from the host

Our regex verbs use a PCRE-flavored syntax borrowed from the host runtime. It's ubiquitous, which is good. It's also opaque and error-prone, which is bad. A parser-combinator library would be more teachable and more composable.

We ship regex because programmers expect it. We know we should ship a combinator library alongside. We haven't. When we do, we'll teach combinators first.

## 17. Error object hierarchy is flat, not typed

Errors are tagged pairs (`(error :kind :message)`) rather than a proper hierarchy of condition types with inheritance. This means catching 'any arithmetic error' requires knowing the specific kind tags.

A richer condition system would let a caller say 'catch any subclass of numeric-error' cleanly. We picked the simpler shape because it fits on a page in the reference. It costs us: some carts have long `cond` chains dispatching on kind tags.

## 18. No compile-time optimization

The interpreter walks the s-expression tree at runtime. There's no ahead-of-time compilation, no JIT, no partial evaluation of hot verbs. This buys us fast iteration — edit a verb, reload, run — and it buys us a small implementation.

It costs us throughput on loop-heavy programs. We are okay with this. the carts are not loop-heavy in the sense that would benefit from compilation. When they become so, we'll revisit. Not before.

## 19. Float printing uses fixed precision, not shortest-round-trip

Floats print with a fixed default precision (12 significant digits). Round-trip exactness (shortest-round-trip printing) isn't the default. If you save `(/ 1.0 3.0)` to a file and read it back, you don't get exactly the same float.

Programs that care set precision explicitly. We know shortest-round-trip is the right default. We use the fixed-precision default because it's what the host runtime gives us cheaply. Fixing this is on the list.

## 20. Single-file book format

A book is one directory of `*.book.slatl` files, one per chapter. This works up to a point — chapters stay under 100 KB and load fast. It breaks down when two authors want to work on different parts of the same chapter simultaneously, or when a chapter grows past its budget.

We haven't shipped a chapter-partitioning scheme because the current shape has been fine for our authoring throughput. We know that won't hold forever.

## 21. No LSP integration

We ship a REPL, a terminal IDE, and a web IDE. We don't ship a Language Server Protocol integration for third-party editors. A reader who lives in their editor doesn't get autocomplete, hover-doc, go-to-definition, or rename-refactor from Motoi Scheme.

We know LSP would help; we haven't built it because the REPL has been sufficient for the users we serve today. If we grew a population of editor-first developers, we'd build the LSP.

## 22. No incremental garbage collection

The garbage collector is a stop-the-world mark-and-sweep. For most carts this is invisible — they don't allocate enough to trigger a noticeable pause. For carts that do — long-running data-processing loops, especially — the pause shows up.

Incremental or generational GC would smooth this. We haven't built it. The complexity cost of generational GC felt higher than the annoyance cost of occasional pauses; if that trade shifts, we'll revisit.

## 23. No tail-position optimization across verb dispatch

Tail calls within a procedure are proper. Tail calls that cross into verb dispatch are re-entered through the interpreter's trampoline rather than being fully eliminated. This means very deep mutual recursion between user procedures and verbs can still grow the trampoline queue.

It hasn't bitten anyone yet, but it's a place where the tail-call story isn't quite as clean as we'd like it to be. We know where the fix goes. We haven't paid the cost.

## 24. No built-in profiler

We ship a `time/measure` verb and that's about it. There's no sampling profiler, no flame-graph output, no per-verb cost attribution. A reader who wants to know why their cart is slow has to instrument by hand.

We know profiler tooling would help; we haven't shipped it because most carts are small enough that eyeballing works. When someone writes a big cart and asks 'why is this slow?' we handle it ad-hoc. Not sustainable at scale.

## 25. MANIFEST format has grown organically

The `MANIFEST.book.slatl` format is what the book loader reads to know which chapters exist and in what order. It has grown organically as we've added books, and now has a handful of optional fields that mean different things in different contexts.

If we started over we'd design the manifest schema up front rather than letting it accrete. We haven't cleaned it up because the messiness is contained to that one file per book and hasn't caused user-visible bugs. It's technical debt we're carrying.

## Closing

Twenty-five compromises, all knowingly made. The next appendix (B) covers where we're happy — same shape, same count, same honesty. Read them together. The full picture of a language is in the pair.
")
